'''''Sea Tails''''' (1983) is a [[video installation]] created as a [[collaboration]] between [[video art]]ist [[Molly Davies (videographer)|Molly Davies]], French artist [[Jackie Matisse]], and composer [[David Tudor]].<ref name="Exhibitions">"[http://www.getty.edu/art/exhibitions/sea_tails/ Sea Tails: A Video Collaboration – July 13 – September 26, 2004 at the Getty Center]", ''Getty.edu''.</ref>

Matisse created four various [[kite]]s, Davies filmed them being 'flown' underwater (drug behind a boat in the Bahamas near Nassau) for eight days, and Tudor simultaneously [[sound recording|recorded]] sound below and above deck, later layered, [[audio mixing (recorded music)|mixed]], and rerecorded the sounds onto three separate [[magnetic tape|tapes]]. This was all combined as a six-[[computer monitor|monitor]] (or three,<ref>"[http://www.getty.edu/news/press/exhibit/seatails.html New Exhibition Recreates Musical Pioneer David Tudor's 20–Year Old Video Collaboration Sea Tails Featuring Sound, Video, and Underwater Kite Sculptures]", ''Getty.edu''.</ref> or rather three-channel video played on six monitors<ref>Pagel, David (August 5, 2004). "[http://articles.latimes.com/2004/aug/05/news/wk-pagel5 An underwater playground: Experimental filmmaking, fabric sculptures and avant-garde music resurface in 'Sea Tails.']", ''Articles.LATimes.com''.</ref>), three-[[studio monitor|channel]] video installation premiered at the [[Pompidou Center]] in 1983 and later exhibited at the [[Getty Center]] in 2004.<ref name="Exhibitions"/>

